This paper discusses the organizational structure of peer production projects, specifically wikis, and how they may conform to Robert Michels' "iron law of oligarchy." This topic falls under the category of computational social science (cs.CY) as it involves the study of social phenomena using computational methods. Additionally, the paper uses empirical data to construct measures of participation, which could fall under the sub-category of social informatics (cs.SI). The study also analyzes the growth of peer production projects, which could be relevant to the sub-category of software development (cs.SD). The paper's focus on organizational structure and leadership could also be relevant to the sub-categories of computer and society (cs.CC) and cryptography and security (cs.CR), as these fields often involve discussions of power dynamics and governance.
